Sweep Impact Analysis for Automated Reserves - BI v3 Implementation

Objective

The goal of the sweep impact analysis is to calculate the sweep impact, defined as the difference between the actual outstanding reserve (primarily driven by the BI v2 model) and the BI v3 model’s predictions. In addition, the analysis will ensure:
	•	Prediction Consistency: BI v3 predictions align with expected values.
	•	Data Integrity in CIM and API: Post-implementation, verify that the variables in the Claim Information Management (CIM) system for each reserve line (RL) match those recorded in the API.

This analysis involves pre-sweep comparison, nightly batch processing during the sweep, and post-implementation testing to ensure accuracy and data consistency throughout the transition.

1. Preparation

	•	Environment Setup: Confirm access to the CC Perf region, a production-like environment to simulate BI v3 predictions accurately.
	•	Script Development:
	•	Develop scripts to add selected exposures to the claim exception batch.
	•	Create automation to run BI v3 predictions for specific exposures to compare them with existing reserves driven by BI v2.

2. Pre-Sweep Impact Analysis

	•	BI v2 vs. BI v3 Prediction Comparison:
	•	Run both BI v2 and BI v3 predictions for a subset of exposures.
	•	Calculate initial differences between the BI v2 actual outstanding reserve and BI v3 predicted reserves to get a preliminary sense of sweep impact.
	•	Error Reconciliation & Data Validation:
	•	Prediction Discrepancies: Document any significant variances between v2 and v3 predictions.
	•	Variable Check: Ensure that variables used in BI v3 predictions align with those in BI v2.
	•	Document Findings: Summarize any variances that may need addressing in the full sweep impact test.

3. Sweep Impact Test (Nightly Batches)

	•	Script Execution for Exposures: Use the developed script to add exposures to the claim exception batch nightly in the CC Perf region.
	•	Nightly Processing in Claim Exception Batch:
	•	Each night, process exposures through the claim exception batch to simulate actual reserve adjustments in the BI v3 environment.
	•	Prediction Validation:
	•	Confirm that BI v3 predictions meet expectations by validating against known data points.
	•	Nightly Error Reconciliation and Data Validation:
	•	Discrepancy Identification: Identify and document differences between the nightly batch BI v3 predictions and actual BI v2-driven reserves.
	•	Variable Consistency: Ensure that variables in CIM for each RL align with those sent to the API.

4. Regular Testing (IT)

	•	Routine Model Validation: Conduct regular checks on the BI v3 model’s predictions to confirm functionality.
	•	Simulated Testing: Run simulations in the production-like environment to detect discrepancies before full deployment.
	•	Discrepancy Logging: Document any inconsistencies in reserve calculations or data transmission between CIM and API.

5. Post-Implementation Testing

	•	Final Sweep Impact Calculation:
	•	After full implementation, calculate the final sweep impact by measuring the difference between actual outstanding reserve (driven by BI v2) and BI v3 predictions.
	•	Comprehensive Data Validation:
	•	Validate all reserve lines (RLs) to ensure that data consistency in CIM matches expected variables in the API.
	•	Stability Monitoring:
	•	Continuously monitor BI v3 model stability to identify any post-deployment discrepancies.

6. Impact Calculation and Analysis

	•	Impact Definition:
	•	Calculate the sweep impact as the difference between the actual outstanding reserve from BI v2 and the predicted reserve from BI v3.
	•	Batch Processing for Analysis:
	•	Run nightly batches (5–7k exposures) to systematically calculate the impact.
	•	Special Case Documentation:
	•	Identify and document cases like closed RLs that may not impact the model directly but could affect total reserve values.

7. Reporting

	•	Generate Sweep Impact Report:
	•	Create a detailed report summarizing the impact difference between BI v2 and BI v3 predictions.
	•	Provide an impact summary for stakeholders, breaking down results by key policy attributes (e.g., region, product type).
	•	Post-Implementation Summary:
	•	Document findings from post-implementation testing, highlighting any final adjustments or recommendations.

8. Code Management and Future Updates

	•	Bitbucket Repository Access:
	•	Access scripts and documentation in the Bitbucket repository for current analysis and future modifications.
	•	Future Update Checklist:
	•	Prediction Logic Adjustments: Update comparison logic if BI v2 model parameters change.
	•	Exposure List Processing: Adjust code if exposure list data changes.
	•	Reporting Modules: Modify the reporting sections to account for new variables.
	•	Data Validation: Ensure future variables or RL conditions are accounted for in the data validation process.

Scenario-Specific Testing Considerations

	•	Testing on Sunday: Quick fixes possible on Monday; limited IT availability.
	•	Full Implementation on Thursday: Efficient resource usage, but high workload if issues arise on Friday.
	•	Manual Validation: Provides high accuracy but requires more resources.

